AGI - Considered an enemy from Ukraine, to which he had just elected said he would no longer send "one bullet"; hostile to the EU, NATO and Kiev - he called "fascists" Ukrainians - supporter of "good relations with the Russian Federation", Fico began his political career in the Communist Party shortly before the Velvet Revolution of 1989 dissolved the former Czechoslovakia.
Today, 60-year-old, he was a representative of Slovakia at the European Court of Human Rights in Strasbourg from 1994 to 2000. In 1999, after not being considered for a position as a minister, he abandoned the Democratic Party of Left (Sdl), political heir of the Communist Party, to found his political formation, the Smer-Social Democrat (Smer-Sd). The gamble gave its fruit in 2006, when Smer-Sd obtained a electoral success that catapulted Fico on the Prime Minister's armchair two years after Slovakia entered the European Union.
Without thinking twice, Fico formed a coalition with the Slovak National Party (Sns) of extreme right, strong anti-refugeed rhetoric and strong populist inclinations. Fico cleverly exploited the 2008 global financial crisis to strengthen its popularity, refusing to impose austerity measures. Slovakia's entry into the Eurozone in 2009 crowned its first four years as prime minister, but the 2010 elections sent him back to the opposition, failing to form a coalition despite the victory.
A new electoral success arrived in 2012, after the fall of a center-right coalition fell down from the charges of corruption. In 2014, however, he was defeated in the presidency by Andrej Kiska, philanthropist and novice of politics. When the refugee crisis overwhelmed Europe in 2015, Fico took a tough position on migrants, refusing to "give origin to a separate Muslim community in Slovakia" and criticizing the EU's quota program to redistribute refugees.
<div </div
&nbsp;
On this platform, Smer won the 2016 elections, but the premier mandate ended two years later following the murder of investigative journalist Jan Kuciak and his fiancée who triggered a wave of anti-government sentiments across Slovakia. The 2020 elections saw him lose but keep his seat in Parliament. His favorite motto describes his political history well: Patience always brings red roses. At the end of April, his populist government adopted a controversial bill on public radiotelevision RTVS, which the premier accuses of lack of objectivity. The text was criticised by the opposition and media rights groups, including Reporters Without Frontiers (RSF).
According to Michal Simecka, opposition party leader Slovakia Progressista (PS), "the government's intention is to create a state television with news that are not public." For another opposition party, SaS (right), "RTVS will become a means of disinformation that will broadcast pro-government propaganda". The RSF organization had already warned against threats affecting the freedom of press in Slovakia, accusing the government to attempt to "impose its control over the contents of public broadcasting" and "political control over the public audiovisual group". &nbsp;
